00:11:13,431 --> 00:11:14,384
Scott: So, that's like, "Ooh.

211
00:11:14,688 --> 00:11:14,830
Scott: Ooh.".

212
00:11:14,870 --> 00:11:16,403
Scott: So, you want to know what's wrong with Nintendo.

213
00:11:16,504 --> 00:11:17,129
Scott: That sort of thing.

214
00:11:17,910 --> 00:11:18,517
Rym: Well, never mind.

215
00:11:18,558 --> 00:11:19,630
Rym: You know, where's my Advance Wars?

216
00:11:20,972 --> 00:11:22,070
Rym: Where's another Advance Wars?

217
00:11:22,430 --> 00:11:26,010
Scott: Why don't they just take every game that they put out in Japan and put it out here?

218
00:11:26,050 --> 00:11:27,650
Scott: They've already made the goddamn games.

219
00:11:28,596 --> 00:11:29,832
Scott: Mother 3.

220
00:11:29,832 --> 00:11:31,690
Rym: Well, look at the Advance Wars situation.

221
00:11:31,910 --> 00:11:34,370
Rym: Because the original, you know, when they released Advance Wars on the Game Boy Advance.

222
00:11:34,390 --> 00:11:35,829
Scott: All the other Advance Wars games.

223
00:11:36,330 --> 00:11:39,110
Rym: But when they released it, it was considered a big gamble.

224
00:11:39,370 --> 00:11:41,410
Rym: And it was pretty much expected to fail.

225
00:11:41,570 --> 00:11:43,225
Rym: They're like, "Americans won't play a turn-based

226
00:11:43,245 --> 00:11:43,528
Rym: game.".

227
00:11:43,870 --> 00:11:44,793
Scott: Yeah, explain to me this.

228
00:11:44,894 --> 00:11:49,730
Scott: Why did they bring Starfy over, but they don't bring Mother 3 or all the other Advance Wars games?

229
00:11:49,750 --> 00:11:55,070
Rym: I think they expected that Starfy would capture the young girl demographic and the casual gamer demographic.

230
00:11:55,350 --> 00:11:55,492
Scott: Oh, yeah.

231
00:11:55,512 --> 00:11:57,030
Scott: I'm sure Starfy did so well.

232
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:58,419
Rym: Look at what they did with Advance Wars.

233
00:11:58,439 --> 00:11:59,849
Rym: They had these Advance Wars games coming over.

234
00:12:00,030 --> 00:12:02,049
Scott: They're getting it right with Layton and Phoenix Wright.

235
00:12:02,970 --> 00:12:05,087
Rym: And the Advance Wars games were cute and puzzle-y.

236
00:12:05,730 --> 00:12:07,410
Rym: And then they tried to make it hardcore.

237
00:12:07,650 --> 00:12:08,970
Rym: Like, remember the most recent Advance Wars?

238
00:12:09,090 --> 00:12:13,330
Scott: Yeah, but they released Days of Ruin also in Japan, if I know correctly.

239
00:12:13,931 --> 00:12:14,414
Rym: Yeah, they did.

240
00:12:14,454 --> 00:12:20,230
Rym: What I'm saying is that when they released that game in the US, when they designed the game, it was a departure from the Advance Wars series.

241
00:12:20,310 --> 00:12:25,470
Rym: I think it was a good departure, but they way changed the style of the game to make it dark and serious.

242
00:12:25,651 --> 00:12:28,290
Rym: And there was a weird trick, and I finally kind of realized why they did this.

243
00:12:28,710 --> 00:12:33,470
Rym: Remember how you could hit R and zoom in, which was basically the so-zoomed-in view that it was stupid?

244
00:12:33,972 --> 00:12:37,350
Rym: You could see, like, two units, but when you zoom in, the units look all different.

245
00:12:38,010 --> 00:12:46,290
Rym: Notice how all the promotional stuff for that game in the US only showed the zoomed-in units, because the zoomed-in units look dark and hardcore and realistic.

246
00:12:46,692 --> 00:12:49,709
Rym: But the zoomed-out units are the cute Advance Wars icons we're used to.

247
00:12:50,290 --> 00:12:57,230
Rym: I think they were very specifically trying to market that game to what they expected were the hardcore sensibilities of Western gamers.

248
00:12:57,852 --> 00:12:59,928
Scott: It's just, they're so incompetent there, right?

249
00:13:00,250 --> 00:13:05,970
Scott: It's like, hello, the reason you already released- That was the fourth Advance Wars game to come out in the United States, right?

250
00:13:06,310 --> 00:13:11,159
Scott: So they already released three in the United States, two for the GBA and one for the DS, and all of them did well.

251
00:13:11,199 --> 00:13:13,029
Scott: That's why they were thinking of bringing another one.

252
00:13:13,511 --> 00:13:15,770
Scott: So why did they change a formula that works?

253
00:13:16,031 --> 00:13:20,170
Scott: This is, I think, the number one problem, is they changed a winning formula, right?

254
00:13:20,210 --> 00:13:20,693
Scott: Zelda 1?

255
00:13:20,693 --> 00:13:22,381
Scott: Oh, it's a winning formula.

256
00:13:22,985 --> 00:13:24,010
Scott: Zelda 2, right?

257
00:13:24,672 --> 00:13:28,130
Scott: Ah, but at the same time- I know you like Zelda 2, but I'm saying they changed a winning formula.

258
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:29,670
Scott: Metroid, Metroid, hey, Metroid?

259
00:13:29,971 --> 00:13:38,230
Rym: No, no, no, Scott, you need to do both, because if you never change the existing formulas, today we'd be playing Ultra Pong Championship Edition DX 2010.

260
00:13:38,230 --> 00:13:39,170
Scott: All right, so that's true.

261
00:13:39,390 --> 00:13:40,210
Scott: And nothing else.

262
00:13:40,530 --> 00:13:40,983
Scott: Okay, no, no, no.

263
00:13:41,550 --> 00:13:49,190
Scott: See, I mean, for example, also there are some changes of formulas that work out, like look at Mario 64, which has now gone into Mario Galaxy.

264
00:13:49,392 --> 00:13:51,150
Scott: Very good change of winning formula, right?

265
00:13:51,290 --> 00:13:54,050
Scott: Metroid Prime, a very good change of winning formula from-.

266
00:13:54,050 --> 00:14:00,130
Rym: Well, all you have to do is when you make a game like that, like say you have a departure, if the core line is still going strong, keep making the core line.

267
00:14:00,290 --> 00:14:04,790
Scott: That's what I was about to say, is if you, you know, if Mario 64 is a success, right?

268
00:14:05,150 --> 00:14:08,370
Scott: Keep it going with the 2D Marios and the 3D Marios.

269
00:14:08,410 --> 00:14:10,410
Scott: Don't stop the 2D Marios, right?

270
00:14:10,710 --> 00:14:16,748
Scott: If the top-down Zelda's doing well, and the 3D Zelda's doing well, keep them both going.

271
00:14:16,828 --> 00:14:17,450
Scott: Don't stop.

272
00:14:17,731 --> 00:14:19,902
Rym: Of course, Scott, your argument will fall flat.

273
00:14:20,063 --> 00:14:21,570
Rym: I just want to ask you one question.

274
00:14:23,311 --> 00:14:28,470
Rym: Is there an Advance Wars game that came out after Days of Ruin that is not in the US, that is in Japan?

275
00:14:28,530 --> 00:14:30,070
Scott: There are plenty of ones that came before.

276
00:14:30,450 --> 00:14:34,150
Rym: Yeah, but the games that come before often will not sell that well.

277
00:14:35,191 --> 00:14:46,170
Rym: Like the Final Fantasies, until this nostalgia trend pushed them up, if you had just released Final Fantasy II and III in like 1998, they probably wouldn't have sold at all.

278
00:14:47,231 --> 00:14:55,627
Rym: People won't go back and play a shitty old game, quote-unquote, unless there's some good marketing effort behind it, or the game has suddenly become classic.

279
00:14:56,770 --> 00:15:03,770
Scott: So anyway, I looked on Wikipedia, right, and there are basically three Advance Wars games that were not released in the US.

280
00:15:04,070 --> 00:15:06,650
Scott: Famicom Wars, Game Boy Wars, and Super Famicom Wars.

281
00:15:06,670 --> 00:15:07,860
Rym: Yeah, they're not that good.

282
00:15:07,940 --> 00:15:09,150
Rym: There's no reason to bring them out.

283
00:15:09,190 --> 00:15:10,827
Scott: They could make a compilation of them.

284
00:15:12,395 --> 00:15:14,790
Scott: Put them at least on the WiiWare/virtual console.

285
00:15:14,951 --> 00:15:21,110
Rym: See, my complaint isn't, it's not like they're making new Advance Wars games, they're not bringing them over, they're just not making Advance Wars games at all.

286
00:15:21,692 --> 00:15:22,569
Scott: They gotta make a new one.

287
00:15:22,937 --> 00:15:23,067
Scott: I know.

288
00:15:23,290 --> 00:15:24,510
Scott: They're making a new Golden Sun.

289
00:15:26,273 --> 00:15:27,230
Scott: Actually, they're done anyway.

290
00:15:27,630 --> 00:15:32,930
Rym: Because Advance Wars has captured my gaming cock more so than any other game has in recent memory.

291
00:15:33,070 --> 00:15:34,350
Scott: Will Wright's as well, apparently.

292
00:15:34,490 --> 00:15:36,330
Rym: Yeah, I was very happy when he said that.

293
00:15:36,590 --> 00:15:41,590
Rym: It vindicated the fact that to this day, I'm trying to get an S on the last three maps in DR.

294
00:15:41,992 --> 00:15:44,530
Scott: Yeah, I think I'm gonna go all S on Pac-Man CEDX.

295
00:15:44,690 --> 00:15:46,389
Scott: If you're not playing Pac-Man CEDX, you suck.

296
00:15:46,872 --> 00:15:47,741
Rym: I got a lot of A's.

297
00:15:47,762 --> 00:15:48,388
Rym: I don't have any S's.

298
00:15:48,570 --> 00:15:49,507
Scott: I got a lot of S's.

299
00:15:49,850 --> 00:15:50,850
Rym: Of course, I haven't been playing that much.

300
00:15:51,773 --> 00:15:53,310
Rym: But, I do want to talk about this briefly.

301
00:15:53,390 --> 00:16:02,050
Rym: There was an article from, actually today, claiming that gamers are abandoning DS and PSP games in favor of smartphones.

302
00:16:02,270 --> 00:16:03,449
Rym: They have some data to back this up.

303
00:16:04,010 --> 00:16:11,190
Rym: But basically, they've said that sales on the DS and the PSP have fallen 13%, and sales of games on smartphones have gone way, way, way, way, way up.

304
00:16:11,733 --> 00:16:13,750
Rym: And they're predicting this huge sea change.

305
00:16:13,990 --> 00:16:18,290
Rym: They're predicting the PSP2 is gonna be dead on arrival, effectively, which, probably.

306
00:16:19,391 --> 00:16:30,070
Rym: But, I think what's actually going on here, and I do believe there is a kind of trend away from the DS PSP, the traditional console, like handheld console.

307
00:16:30,734 --> 00:16:32,130
Rym: But I don't think it's a sea change.

308
00:16:32,311 --> 00:16:37,350
Rym: I think consoles like the DS have started capturing this so-called casual gamer market.

309
00:16:38,130 --> 00:16:40,230
Rym: And those people didn't have any options before.

310
00:16:40,370 --> 00:16:41,907
Rym: They're like, "Ooh, I want to play these silly little

311
00:16:41,927 --> 00:16:42,129
Rym: games."

312
00:16:42,190 --> 00:16:43,270
Rym: And they got a DS because it was cheap.

313
00:16:44,091 --> 00:16:45,309
Rym: Everyone has a smartphone now.

314
00:16:45,670 --> 00:16:52,910
Rym: Those people aren't even going to bother buying a DS or buying a game or anything, when cheap, crappy, like one-off games are a dollar on their iPhone.

315
00:16:53,271 --> 00:16:53,855
Scott: That is true.

316
00:16:53,875 --> 00:16:56,010
Scott: I mean, I can think there's a bunch of factors, right?

317
00:16:56,694 --> 00:16:58,290
Scott: The one you pointed out, I definitely agree with.

318
00:16:58,450 --> 00:17:03,706
Scott: I definitely agree that there's a problem when I can get Choo-Choo Rocket on my iPhone for a dollar, but $30 on the DS.

319
00:17:05,270 --> 00:17:12,109
Rym: There's the fact that there's been a relatively small number of compelling games on handheld consoles in the last year?

320
00:17:12,490 --> 00:17:18,676
Scott: That's another thing I was gonna bring up, is that the number of games for the handheld that are like, "Oh man, I gotta get that,"?

321
00:17:19,040 --> 00:17:20,490
Scott: not too many of them, right?

322
00:17:20,910 --> 00:17:29,274
Scott: You know, the ones I can think of right away are like, there was a... That's kind of old, right?

323
00:17:29,314 --> 00:17:36,410
Scott: There was the Miles Edgeworth game, there was a new Layton game, and the Golden Sun DS, and Dragon Quest IX, a lot of people are on that, you know?

324
00:17:36,630 --> 00:17:37,319
Rym: Yeah, but how few is that?

325
00:17:38,370 --> 00:17:38,458
Rym: Four.

326
00:17:39,330 --> 00:17:42,490
Scott: Meanwhile, on the iPhone, there's like a zillion games, and they're all like a dollar or three dollars.

327
00:17:42,570 --> 00:17:46,050
Rym: We're definitely very choosy in the games we play, so let's say we expand that.

328
00:17:46,390 --> 00:17:49,790
Rym: Triple that number, assuming there's a bunch of games we don't care about that other people care about.

329
00:17:49,850 --> 00:17:51,389
Rym: That's still a tiny number of releases.

330
00:17:51,790 --> 00:17:52,650
Scott: Yeah, that are worth playing.

331
00:17:52,690 --> 00:17:57,810
Scott: And I think the other thing is, telling you from my personal experience, that someone has an iPhone and a DS, right?

332
00:17:59,052 --> 00:18:01,467
Scott: My DS was stolen, and I was thinking, "Should I really replace

333
00:18:01,527 --> 00:18:01,568
Scott: it?".

334
00:18:02,191 --> 00:18:04,966
Scott: And the thing is, I replaced it because I got a piracy card, right?

335
00:18:05,810 --> 00:18:18,570
Scott: It wouldn't be worth it without one of those, because there's a bunch of games that are sort of like, I would maybe kind of want to try them out, don't really want to finish them on the DS, that really aren't worth paying full price for.

336
00:18:18,711 --> 00:18:22,190
Scott: Notice I did pay full price for Golden Sun, which is totally, you know, that's my game.

337
00:18:22,811 --> 00:18:26,150
Scott: But I play games on the DS and the iPhone, and really, it's changed.

338
00:18:26,270 --> 00:18:31,170
Scott: I used to bring the DS all the way around with me when I had a regular phone, and I'd play that all the time.

339
00:18:31,731 --> 00:18:37,310
Scott: But now, if I'm on the subway, I'm playing some stupid games on the phone.

340
00:18:37,472 --> 00:18:38,869
Scott: I'm not bringing the DS with me.

341
00:18:39,091 --> 00:18:41,850
Scott: The DS, I mostly use that for playing in bed.

342
00:18:42,111 --> 00:18:46,190
Scott: I use the DS the same time that I would read a book or read a comic book.

343
00:18:46,411 --> 00:18:48,120
Rym: Remember back when we had the long commutes?

344
00:18:48,160 --> 00:18:50,130
Rym: Like, my DS was my primary console.

345
00:18:50,250 --> 00:18:54,210
Rym: I would come home, sit down, and just play my DS for a couple hours.

346
00:18:54,450 --> 00:18:56,150
Scott: Back in those days, I would do the same exact thing.

347
00:18:56,250 --> 00:19:00,390
Scott: But nowadays, the DS, I'm not really using it portably that much.

348
00:19:00,530 --> 00:19:06,550
Scott: I mean, the portability factor is basically, ah, I can play this on the couch or in bed, as opposed to sitting up at the desk.

349
00:19:06,570 --> 00:19:07,694
Rym: Now, I do have a different situation.

350
00:19:07,734 --> 00:19:11,950
Rym: My commute is so short, I don't have any incentive to play phone games or anything.

351
00:19:12,091 --> 00:19:13,910
Scott: The thing is, my commute is so short.

352
00:19:14,691 --> 00:19:20,250
Scott: But even just standing on the subway platform for five minutes, there are games that are that small that I play.

353
00:19:20,370 --> 00:19:22,322
Rym: Yeah, I listen to music or I read.

354
00:19:22,342 --> 00:19:23,670
Rym: I just do other things.

355
00:19:25,433 --> 00:19:38,690
Rym: But what's interesting here is that I think all these predictions of a sea change, what's really going on, and we talked about this at PAX in all of our panels, is that people keep saying the market is moving toward casual games and phones and simple games.

356
00:19:39,912 --> 00:19:52,210
Rym: I really think that the majority of those people were not gamers in the sense that there is one demographic of gamers that will always want to play so-called hardcore real games.

357
00:19:52,630 --> 00:19:58,250
Rym: And all these people are newcomers who really, what they're playing don't compete with the other games.

358
00:19:58,691 --> 00:20:00,469
Rym: They're two completely separate markets.

359
00:20:01,330 --> 00:20:06,690
Rym: People might cross over between one or the other, but most of this competition, I think, is false.

360
00:20:06,851 --> 00:20:14,109
Rym: No one's really moving to the iPhone saying, "I'm going to buy all my games on the iPhone now," because there aren't that many good games on the iPhone.

361
00:20:14,752 --> 00:20:17,341
Scott: No, no one's moving to the iPhone for games.

362
00:20:17,401 --> 00:20:19,669
Scott: They have an iPhone and they get games.

363
00:20:21,231 --> 00:20:27,770
Scott: People had cell phones before, regular phones, and even on the shittiest phone you can get, you can buy Tetris on there for a couple bucks.

364
00:20:27,930 --> 00:20:28,437
Scott: So people go, "Ooh,

365
00:20:28,457 --> 00:20:28,822
Scott: Tetris.".

366
00:20:29,511 --> 00:20:30,949
Scott: But this is starting to be a big problem.

367
00:20:31,492 --> 00:20:39,301
Rym: And that pundits and industry analysts and game designers are looking at all these numbers and saying, "Yeah, there's like 20 billion people playing social games.

368
00:20:39,321 --> 00:20:40,145
Rym: We've got to get on that shit.

369
00:20:40,165 --> 00:20:40,788
Rym: That's the future of

370
00:20:40,808 --> 00:20:41,130
Rym: gaming.".

371
00:20:41,150 --> 00:20:54,750
Scott: Well, the reason that there's that perception is if you're a game development company, you make games, you say, "Huh, I could make big expensive games and then try to get lucky and sell enough copies to make a profit, which potentially could be big, but probably not.

372
00:20:55,111 --> 00:21:03,889
Scott: Or with the same exact people at this company and the same exact talent and equipment, the resources that I have, I could devote these resources to making tiny shit games and make more

373
00:21:03,929 --> 00:21:04,090
Scott: money.".

374
00:21:04,670 --> 00:21:12,030
Scott: So it's basically a diversion of resources on the developer level and the publisher level that is moving from one to the other.

375
00:21:12,110 --> 00:21:13,810
Scott: In all other ways, there isn't a connection.

376
00:21:13,950 --> 00:21:14,974
Rym: Let me analogize this.

377
00:21:15,034 --> 00:21:17,563
Rym: This would be like a guy who owns a McDonald's, let's just say.

378
00:21:20,051 --> 00:21:20,878
Rym: He owns a McDonald's.

379
00:21:20,919 --> 00:21:21,685
Rym: That's his franchise.

380
00:21:21,726 --> 00:21:22,190
Rym: It makes money.

381
00:21:22,490 --> 00:21:25,230
Rym: He's looking at it and he sees a pita pit next door.

382
00:21:25,350 --> 00:21:27,497
Rym: He's like, "Man, pita pit's where the money's at.

383
00:21:27,738 --> 00:21:30,767
Rym: I should turn my McDonald's into a pita pit because competition,

384
00:21:30,807 --> 00:21:31,128
Rym: whatever.".

385
00:21:31,811 --> 00:21:35,346
Rym: Or, "Yeah, that car dealership makes way more money than my McDonald's.

386
00:21:35,427 --> 00:21:35,969
Rym: I should do that

387
00:21:36,009 --> 00:21:36,230
Rym: instead.".

388
00:21:36,230 --> 00:21:43,659
Scott: Well, the difference is the resources a McDonald's has, you can't just change the sign outside of McDonald's and suddenly it becomes a pita pit.

389
00:21:43,679 --> 00:21:47,860
Scott: You need completely different equipment in the kitchen, completely different new training of the employees.

390
00:21:48,322 --> 00:21:49,066
Scott: You need all this stuff.

391
00:21:50,373 --> 00:22:03,480
Scott: But if you have people who know how to program games and computers, you can divert those resources to a lot of different ends without really having to do a whole lot of work other than saying, "Stop making the big fancy PS3 game.

392
00:22:03,781 --> 00:22:05,165
Scott: Make Tetris for the iPhone

393
00:22:05,205 --> 00:22:05,366
Scott: instead.".

394
00:22:06,990 --> 00:22:12,950
Scott: And those same people with just nothing except deciding to can switch over and do something different.

395
00:22:13,050 --> 00:22:19,750
Scott: So if you can do that and the different thing you can do is more likely to be more profitable, how can you not?

396
00:22:20,330 --> 00:22:29,996
Rym: So I think the real root of all this is that in the end, the games that we care about, the so-called good games in our opinion, they're going to be made primarily by kings.

397
00:22:30,638 --> 00:22:34,790
Rym: And the shit games, the so-called casual social games, are going to be made by rich people.

398
00:22:35,010 --> 00:22:37,577
Scott: But even look out, you know, the Madden still makes a ton of money.

399
00:22:37,637 --> 00:22:42,290
Scott: The Call of Duty is like the hugest story of the past year or two, making so much money.

400
00:22:42,290 --> 00:22:44,126
Rym: Oh yeah, but they're relatively few and also...

401
00:22:44,631 --> 00:22:46,089
Scott: Portal 2 is going to rake it in.

402
00:22:46,130 --> 00:22:54,710
Rym: But Scott, I note that most of that industry is built on the backs of overworked, underpaid programmers who eventually are going to freak their shit out and quit.

403
00:22:55,090 --> 00:22:58,167
Scott: Well look at EA, what happened there with the overworking situation?

404
00:22:58,850 --> 00:23:00,182
Rym: Look at every game company.

405
00:23:00,202 --> 00:23:01,030
Rym: It's a serious problem.

406
00:23:01,090 --> 00:23:03,890
Scott: Well, I think there's also the Minecraft situation you can't ignore.

407
00:23:03,950 --> 00:23:04,413
Rym: That's a king.

408
00:23:05,198 --> 00:23:05,642
Rym: He's a king.

409
00:23:05,722 --> 00:23:06,789
Rym: Good games are coming out of kings.

